Graphs

  • complete graph

  • tree

  • clique

  • hamiltonian cycle

  • induced subgraph : G[W] is the graph induced by a set of vertices W

  • steiner triple system, STS

    STS(3)={{0,1,2}}

    ∃STS(n)⟺n mod 6=1 or 3

  • *Latin square

    L=n×n×Σ={(row,col,content)}

    L=set system(V,B),V=X×{1,2,3},B={3-subsets of V}

    Example,

    (abba)

  • *transversal design

    TD=set system(V,B,X),|V|=3n,B={3-subsets of V},X={X1,X2,X3} a partition of V

    Example,

    (V={1,2,3,4,5,6},B={{1,3,5},{2,3,6},{1,4,6},{2,4,5}},X={{1,2},{3,4},{5,6}})

     

data structures:

  • incidence matrix : a |B|×|V| matrix

    Example, V={1,2,3,4},B={{1,2},{2,3},{2,3,4}}

    (110001100111)

  • adjacency matrix

  • adjacency list

  • point-block incidence graph

 

Graph Isomorphism

  • isomorphism / isomorphic
  • automorphism

  • invariant inducing function

    D:V→{0,1,...,k} is an invariant inducing function, if ϕD(G)=[|P[0]|,|P[1]|,...,|P[k]|] is an invariant (under isomorphism), where P[i]={v∈V:D(v)=i}.

 

Vertex Partition

  • induced vertex partition

    Given function D:F×V→{0,1,2,...,k}, F is a family of graphs on vertices V .

    partition induced by D is PD=[PD[0],...,PD[k]],where PD[i]={v:D(G,v)=i}

  • discrete partition : finest

  • unit partition : only 1 block

  • equitable partition :

    graph G=(V,E), adjacency / neighbor of u, NG(u)={x∈V:{u,x}∈E}.

    partition P is equitable ⟺ Given any i, ∀u,v∈P[i],∀j,|NG(v)∩P[j]|=|NG(u)∩P[j]|.

  • matrix associated to an equitable partition :

    Given equitable partition P with k blocks, matrix MP∈Nk×k, MP[i,j]=|NG(v)∩P[j]|, where v∈P[i].

    Remark:

    Well-defined by definition of equitable partition

  • (ordered) partition refinement

  • set

  • *multi-set

    In book, msb = least number

*Code

  • *(block) code :

    q-ary (block) code C of length n is a non-empty subset of (Σq)n , where Σq is a finite alphabet of size q

    Example, C={000,001,201}⊆Z34 is a ternary code of length 3

    Equivalence of code :

    C1≅C2

    ⟺ C1 can be obtained by permuting coordinates and permuting Σq from C2

    Example:

    C1={000,011,201}→position1↔2{000,101,021}→value1↔2{000,202,012}=C2

  • *linear code :

    (linear) code C of length n over field F is a subspace of Fn

    Representation of linear code :

    1. generator sets
    2. generator matrix
    Equivalence of linear code :

    1. Permutation Equivalent

      C1≅πC2

      ⟺∃ permutation matrix P,s.t.

      ∀G1, generator matrix of C1,G1P is a generator matrix of C2.

      ⟺ rearranging columns of generator matrix of G1 gives generator matrix of G2

       

    2. Monomially Equivalent

      Def (Monomial matrix) square matrix A is monomial ⟺ A has exactly 1 nonzero entry in each row and column.

      C1≅MC2

      ⟺∃ monomial matrix M,s.t.

      ∀G1, generator matrix of C1,G1M is a generator matrix of C2.

      ⟺ scalar (in field F) multiple and permutation of columns of generator matrix of G1 gives generator matrix of G2

      Example :

       

      Remark :

      ≅π⟹≅M

       

    3. Code Equivalent

      C1≅C2

      ⟺∃ monomial matrix M,∃ automorphism of Fq,σ, s.t.

      ∀G1, generator matrix of C1,G1Mσ is a generator matrix of C2.

      ⟺ scalar (in field F) multiple, permutation of columns of generator matrix of G1and automorphism of alphabet, gives generator matrix of G2.

      Example :

      <001,211,120>≅<002,122,210>

     

Types of Problems

  • decision problem

  • search problem

  • optimization problem

    • objective function
    • feasibility function

    (generic optimization)

    instance: A finite set S
              an objective function P : S → Z.
              a finite set of feasibility functions Fi : S → Z, 1 ≤ i ≤ m.
    solution: x in S, s.t. P(x) maximal, Fi(x)≥0

 

Complexity Class

  • *Polynomial transformation : P1∝P2⟺ any instance of P1 can be transformed to instance of P2 in polynomial time and they share the same "yes"/"no" answer.
  • *Turing reduction : P2 with algorithm A2, P1∝TP2 ⟺ ∃ algorithm A1 that solves P1 and uses A2 as sub-routine.

  • exhaustive search

Combinatorial Problems & Algorithms

Generation

All Subsets

xxxxxxxxxx
Instance: a set S
Solution: generate all subsets of set S

characteristic vector : !! Notice n=3, {1,2}->[1,1,0]

lexicographic ordering

  • ranking: easy

  • unranking: easy

  • successor: 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    for i= n -> 0
        if i not in S
            S.add(i)
            remove all number in S bigger than i

     

minimal change ordering

  • ranking: 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1.concatenate top 0
    2.add 2 consecutive bit
    3.get correponding bit in rank in binary

    Example: {1,2,5} -> 11001 -> 011001 -> 10101 ->21

  • unranking: 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1.make rank to binary
    2.add all bits left to current bit (including current bit)
    3.get correponding bit in characteristic vector

    Example: 21 -> 10101 -> 11001 -> {1,2,5}

  • successor: 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1a. if even weight -> flip last bit;
    1b. if odd weight -> right to left, flip bit after the first 1

    Example: {1,2,5} -(odd)-> {1,2,4,5}

 

k-subset

xxxxxxxxxx
Instance: a set S
Solution: generate all k-subsets of set S
lexicographic ordering

  • ranking: rank(S)=∑i=1k∑j=si−1+1si−1(k−in−j)

  • unranking: left to right, judge whether (x=1 to n) is at that place by comparing (k−in−j).

  • successor: right to left, increase first number that can be increased, reset number behind it to its successors.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    for i= k -> 0
        if S[i] < n-i
            S[i]+=1
            reset number after position i

     

Permutation

xxxxxxxxxx
Instance: a set S
Solution: generate all permutations of elements in S

 

lexicographic ordering

  • successor: 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1. from right to left, find longest decreasing suffix
    2. exchange non-decreasing element with its predecessor in the suffix
    3. sort suffix in increasing order

    Example: [1,3,5,4,2] -> [1,4,5,3,2] -> [1,4,2,3,5]

  • *rank:

    rank(π,n)=(π[0]−1)(n−1)!+rank(π′,n−1)where π′[i]={π[i+1]−1if π[i+1]>π[0]π[i+1]if π[i+1]<π[0]

    Example:

    [1,3,5,4,2] -> 0+[2,4,3,1] -> 0+6+[3,2,1] -> 0+6+4+[2,1] -> 0+6+4+1+0=11

  • *unrank:

    factorial representation of a number, r=∑i=1n−1(di×i!),0≤di≤i

    xxxxxxxxxx
    p[n-1]=1
    for i=n-2 to 0
        calculate d_i
        p[i]=d_i+1
        for j=i+1 to n-1
            if p[j]>d_i, then p[j]++

    Example:

    unrank(11,5)--> [?,?,?,?,1], r'=0+6+4+1 --> [?,?,?,2,1], r''=0+6+4 --> [?,?,3,2,1], r'''=0+6 --> [?,2,3(+1),2(+1),1], r=0 --> [1,2(+1),4(+1),3(+1),1(+1)]=[1,3,5,4,2]

Backtrack

Knapsack

xxxxxxxxxx
Instance: K=(P,W,M), P=list of profits, W=list of weight, M=maximum weight
Solution: a list of items taken S, total weight <= M
(Decision) Is there a solution S with given profit p?
(Optimization) Find solution S with maximum profit
Backtrack

iterate over all combinations of choices of items

Backtrack with Choice set

Cl={items with larger No. and weight not exceeded}, current weight maintained

*Backtrack with bounding

sort items according to profitweight

using RKnapsack as an upper bound

All Cliques

xxxxxxxxxx
Instance: a graph G
Solution: a list of all cliques in Graph
  • Cl=AX[l−1]∩BX[l−1]∩Cl−1, AX[l−1]={vertices adjacent to X[l−1]}, BX[l−1]={vertices > X[l−1]} for eliminating repeated cliques
  • Nl=AX[l−1]∩Nl−1={nodes that can potentially added to form bigger clique} partially 'maximal' clique ⟺ Nl=∅

 

Size of Backtrack Tree

xxxxxxxxxx
Instance: a backtrack algorithm/tree
Solution: number of nodes estimated

  • one path: go through a certain path estimate corresponding to branch number

    estimate(L2)=1+2+4+8=15

  • several paths: calculate the average, or calculate the weighted average by the ratio of probability of selecting that path.

    Theorem the expectance of estimated tree size = real size

     

Exact Cover

xxxxxxxxxx
Instance: (X,B), B={subsets of X}
Solution: a exact cover S⊆B, S consists of disjoint sets, ⋃S=V
Transforms to clique problem

Given set system S=(X,B), construct graph G=(V,E), with

  • vertices: V=B
  • edges: E={{Bi,Bj}∈B2:Bi∩Bj=∅(disjoint)}

Lemma exact cover of S⟹a clique in G=(V,E) that covers all X

 

Backtrack

The idea is the same as solving clique problem.

But now, we do NOT need to find all the cliques, what we need is a clique covering all numbers if exists.

  • First, sort the blocks V=B in lexicographic decreasing order
  • Cl′=AX[l−1]∩GX[l−1]∩Cl−1′, AX[l−1]={vertices adjacent to X[l−1]}, GX[l−1]={vertices > X[l−1]} (since vertices are subsets, >=>lex) for eliminating repeated cliques, as usual.
  • maintaining variable r=least number that is NOT covered in current cover
  • Cl=Cl′∩Hr , Hr={blocks whose least element is r}

 

Maximum Clique (with bounding)

xxxxxxxxxx
Instance: a graph G
Solution: maximum size of clique exists in Graph

The same as all clique algorithm but with bounding.

xxxxxxxxxx
...
Compute choice set C_l
b = B(X)
for each x in C_l
    if b<= currOpt then return
    x_l = x
    next iteration
general bound

B(X)=|X|+bounding(G,X), bounding(G,X) is yet to be designed

Remark: "b≤currOpt" need to be checked every cycle, since during next iteration, currOpt may decrease and make "b≤currOpt" satisfied in later cycles

 

size bound

B(X)=|X|+|Cl|

 

greedy color

Lemma G has a k-coloring ⟹ G don't have clique of size >k

a greedy heuristic algorithm for finding a small coloring (NOT solving coloring problem, but finding a upper bound for color needed)

xxxxxxxxxx
GreedyColor(V,E)
    k=0 //colors used currently
    for i=0 to |V|-1
        find an existing color that all neighbours of i is NOT in that color
        if not found
            add 1 color
            color i with new color
            k++
    return k

 

sampling bound

run GreedyColor before hand

B(X)=|X|+|{Color[x]:x∈Cl}|

 

greedy bound

B(X)=|X|+GreedyColor(G[Cl]), G[Cl] is the induced graph

 

Heuristic Search

Generic Optimization

xxxxxxxxxx
instance: A finite set S
          an objective function P : S → Z.
          a finite set of feasibility functions Fi : S → Z, 1 ≤ i ≤ m.
solution: x in S, s.t. P(x) maximal, Fi(x)≥0

 

neighbourhood function

computing neighborhood of a (partial) solution

remark:

  1. N(X)=(partial) solutions "close to" current solution X
  2. fast to compute
  3. should be designed that possible to achieve real optimal with finite steps of applying neighborhood function

N(X) may give infeasible solutions

 

neighbourhood seach

4 classic strategies

  • exhaustive

    • steepest ascend
    • best neighbour

  • randomized

    • random improvement

      xxxxxxxxxx
      r = random neighbour
      if r improves current solution
          return  r 
      else 
          return "fail"

    • random feasible

remark:

  1. should be designed to only give feasible solution or "fail"

 

Generic Heuristic
xxxxxxxxxx
GenericHeuristic(c_max)
    select X = initial solution
    while c < c_max
        Y = NeighbourhoodSearch(X)
        if Y is not fail
            X=Y
            if Y improves OptX
                OptX=Y
        c++
    return OptX

Travelling Salesman Problem

xxxxxxxxxx
instance: complete graph Kn
          cost function c: VxV->R
solution: hamiltonian circuit X, C(X) is minimized
2-opt move
MGK recombine

  • Mutation/Neighborhood search:

    2-opt move

    steepest ascend among all 2-opt moves

  • Initial population is done by Permutation Unrank

  • Mating:

    1. Partially match over

    2. MGK recombine

      variable j=random position, l=random length

      the segment S is first copied to the beginning of a new child, then completed to a feasible solution by appending the nodes of the other parent not in S in the order in which they appear.

      Example:

      j=2, l=4, x=[1,2,3,4,5,6,7], y=[2,1,5,3,7,6,4]

      mgk(x,y)=[1,5,3,7,2,4,6], [2,3,4,5,1,7,6]

Steiner Triple System

Stinson's Algorithm (hill climbing)
xxxxxxxxxx
instance: n
solution: construct an STS(n)

Lemma STS(n)=(V,B), then every points in V occurs in exactly r=n−12 blocks and |B|=n(n−1)6

Theorem ∃STS(n)⟺n mod 6=1 or 3

xxxxxxxxxx
Switch()
    randomly choose live point x
    randomly choose y,z, s.t. (x,y), (x,z) are live
    if (y,z) is live
        add block {x,y,z}
    else
        find and delete block {y,z,w}, add block {x,y,z}
xxxxxxxxxx
Stinson()
    while |B| < n(n-1)/6
        do Switch()
    return (V,B)

general scheme

Certificate (for tree)

Cert:F→{0,1}∗, F is a famlily of trees, Cert(T)=a balanced binary string of length 2|V|

Encoding
xxxxxxxxxx
Label all vertices with '01'.
While there are more than 2 vertices in G:
    for each non-leaft x of G do
    1. Let Y be the set of labels of the leaves adjacent to x and the label of x with initial 0 and trailing 1 deleted from x;
    2. Replace the label of x with the concatenation of the labels in Y, sorted in increasing lexicographic order, with a 0 prepended and a 1 appended.
    3. Remove all leaves adjacent to x.
If there is only one vertex x left, report x’s label as the certificate.
If there are 2 vertices x and y left, concatenate x and y in increasing lexicographic order, and report it as the certificate.

in book: given order = lexicographic increasing order

 

Decoding

0=up, 1=down,

attach nodes correspond to mountain range at different see level (depth of tree).

 

Certificate (for general graph)

Cert1

  • adjacency matrix

  • adjacency number

    Num(G)= binary string obtained by concatenate (upper half of) adjacency matrix column by column

    Example :

    (0111100010011010)→110101(column by column)

  • minimum num:

    Cert1=min{Num(π(G)):π∈Sym(V)}

    a certificate that difficult to compute. (NP-hard)

 

Cert2

Instead of going through all permutations, possible to go through a less class of permutations Π(G), according to structure of a particular graph G.

Recall: (equitable partition)

graph G=(V,E), adjacency of u, NG(u)={x∈V:{u,x}∈E}. partition P is equitable ⟺ Given any i, ∀u,v∈B[i],∀j,|NG(v)∩B[j]|=|NG(u)∩B[j]|.

Recall: (matrix associated to an equitable partition)

Given equitable partition P with k blocks, matrix MP∈Nk×k, MP[i,j]=|NG(v)∩P[j]|, where v∈P[i].

Similar to what is done in Cert1,

Nume(G,P)= binary string obtained by concatenate (upper half of) equitable matrix column by column.

Example : (the notation in the picture is a bit different)

 

Lemma If P is a discrete partition,

then P corresponds to a permutation π : P[i]={π[i]}, and Nume(G,P)=Num(π(G))

 

equitablization

Given a set of vertices S in graph G, define the equitablize function DG,S:V→N, DG,S(v)=|NG(v)∩S|

Given an (ordered) partition P,

xxxxxxxxxx
copy and push blocks of P into stack S
While S not empty
    B=S.pop()
    refine P by D_{G,B}
    push newly splitted blocks into S

Example,

initial partition P={{1,5},{2,3,4,6}} (NOT equitable), after refining, P={{1},{5},{4},{6},{2,3}}

Remark:

If P is a unit partition (P={V}), then refine P by DG,V is equivalent to refining by degree. (Since DG,V(v)= degree of v)

computing Cert2

Remark:

Actually, the comparation is done not when the whole certificate is computed, but every time the partial certificate is known. This can prune the search tree partially

 

Example :

Remark:

Notice when run this for complete graph, it will still go through Sym(V).

 

*pruning with automorphisms

Lemma Num(π(G))=Num(π′(G))⟹ϕ=π∘π′−1is an automorphism

  1. find automorphisms by Lemma
  2. generate automorphism group using discovered automorphism as generators
  3. use known automorphisms to prune the search

 

*Isomorphism of Others

colored graphs

preserving colors

 

Set systems

Isomorphism of set system can be transformed to isomorphism of (bipartite) graph.

Given set system S=(X,B), define bipartite graph G=(V,E), where V=X∪B, E={(x,B)∈X×B:x∈B}.

Theorem S1≅S2⟹G1≅G2

Remark:

Converse is NOT true

But if a color function is added to indicate blocks and vertices,

 

Given set system S=(X,B), define colored (bipartite) graph G=(V,E,f), where

  • vertices, V=X∪B,
  • edges, E={(x,B)∈X×B:x∈B}
  • (vertex) coloring, f(X)={0},f(B)={1}, that is, only 2 colors indicating blocks and vertices.

Theorem S1≅S2⟺G1≅G2

Example,

S1=(V1,B1),V1={1,2,3},B1={{1},{1,2},{1,3}}

S2=(V2,B2),V2={1,2,3},B2={{3},{2},{1,2,3}}

 

Lemma S1=(X,B1)≅S2=(X,B2)⟺ G1≅G2 with respect to partition P1=[X,B1],P2=[X,B2]. And for isomorphism ϕ:G1→G2 with respect to P1,P2, ϕ|X is an isomorphism of S1,S2.

 

Codes

Isomorphism of codes can be transformed to isomorphism of colored graph.

Given q-ary code C⊆Zqn, define coloured graph G=(V,E,f) with

  • vertices, V=C∪A, where A=({1,2,...,n}×Zq),
  • edges, E={{x,(i,x[i])}:x∈C,i∈{1,2,...,n}}∪{{(j,a),(j,b)}:j∈{1,2,...,n},a,b∈Zq}
  • (vertex) colouring, f(C)={0},f(A)={1}, that is, only 2 colors indicating code elements and positionals.

Example, code elements positionals

This graph can represent {000,011,220}≅{000,110,022}≅{111,221,100}...
